Many other comedians were filmed but not included due to time constraints. According to a letter from Penn Jillette to critic [[Roger Ebert]], [[Buddy Hackett]] and [[Rodney Dangerfield]] were intended to be included, but died before they could be filmed. Jillette also indicated that, this being [[Johnny Carson]]'s favorite joke, Carson was also invited to appear, but declined.<ref>{{cite web | author=Penn Jillette | title=Letter to Roger Ebert | url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050821/ANSWERMAN/508210304/1023 | date=21 August 2005 | work=Movie Answer Man | publisher=RogerEbert.com | accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>

==Joe Franklin controversy==
In the film, [[Sarah Silverman]] tells a version of the joke as if it were autobiographical and she had been one of the "Aristocrats" performers as a child.  Silverman builds the story to include her family being booked on veteran talk show host [[Joe Franklin]]'s show, and ends with her [[punch line]]: a [[deadpan]] allegation that Franklin had raped her during a phony rehearsal for the show. ''[[The New Yorker]]'' reported that Silverman's telling of the joke led Franklin, who is also featured in the film, to consider filing a defamation lawsuit against the comedian.<ref>{{cite news | author=Dana Goodyear | title=Quiet Depravity | url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/10/24/051024fa_fact | work=The New Yorker | date=24 October 2005| accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>

On the April 20, 2011 episode of the WFMU show ''[[Seven Second Delay]]'', Franklin jokes that he had been so successful lately because he sued Silverman.<ref>{{cite interview | subject=Andy co-hosts with Joe Franklin at the UCB Theater  | interviewer=| title= | url=http://www.wfmu.org/playlists/shows/40025 | format=audio/transcript | program=''Seven Second Delay with Ken and Andy'' | callsign=WFMU | date=20 April 2011 | accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>

==AMC banning==
The theater chain [[AMC Theatres|AMC]] refused to show the movie on any of its 3,500+ screens. Although AMC claimed the decision was due to the film's limited appeal,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-07-14/business/0507140212_1_amc-blase-aristocrats |title=AMC theater patrons won't be getting joke |publisher=Chicago Tribune |date=2005-07-14 |accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref> co-producer Penn Jillette commented to [[MSNBC]]: "It's the kind of thing that makes you go 'Come on, play fair.' It's not like we're trying to slide this by anybody by calling it ''[[The Love Bug|Love Bug]] 2: Herbie Takes It Up the Ass''."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/2005/12/30/censored-in-2005/ |title=Censored in 2005 |publisher=TMZ.com |date=2005-12-30 |accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Censoring-Aristocrats-1341.html |title=Censoring Aristocrats |publisher=CinemaBlend.com |date=2005-07-12 |accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref>

==Friars Club roast footage==
{{see also|9/11 humor}}
The film includes footage of [[Gilbert Gottfried]]'s telling of the joke at a [[Comedy Central]]/[[New York Friars' Club|Friars' Club]] [[roast (comedy)|roast]] of [[Hugh Hefner]] which had been almost entirely censored when aired on television. Taped not long after the [[September 11 attacks]], the incident occurred at a time when, according to one of the commentators in the ''Aristocrats'' film, entertainers were uncertain how much comedy was allowed in the aftermath of the attacks. Gottfried followed [[Rob Schneider]], who had received mixed results with his stand-up comedy performance in Hefner's honor. Gottfried began his performance with a joke in which he claimed to have to catch a late flight out of town but was worried because his flight "had a connection at the [[Empire State Building]]."  The joke, a reference to 9/11, was poorly received by the audience, who showered Gottfried with boos and cries of "too soon."  In response, Gottfried told an obscenity-filled rendition of the [[The Aristocrats (joke)|Aristocrats joke]]. According to the film, the telling was as much a cathartic experience for the audience as it was a shocking one, regardless of whether viewers were familiar with the joke or not. During his performance, Gottfried told the audience "They might have to clean this up for TV."

